@mlundblad

I searched for localization and found `Number.prototype.toLocaleString()`. I added the below code right after line 149 and got the localization of numbers working. (I had to import GLib for getting locale and gettext for conversion to translatable template string)

```
        let locale = GLib.get_language_names()[0];

        // Convert to Canonical Locale, and replace '_' with '-' since EcmaScript spec 
        // allows only hyphen separated locales
        let canonicalLocale = Intl.getCanonicalLocales(locale.substring(0, 5).replace("_", "-"))

        let localeOptions = {
            minimumFractionDigits: 2,
            maximumFractionDigits: 5 
        };
        let startLat = startLocation.latitude.toLocaleString(canonicalLocale, localeOptions)
        let startLang = startLocation.longitude.toLocaleString(canonicalLocale, localeOptions)

        let endLat = endLocation.latitude.toLocaleString(canonicalLocale, localeOptions)
        let endLang = endLocation.longitude.toLocaleString(canonicalLocale, localeOptions)
        return _("Route from (%s, %s) to (%s, %s)").format(startLat, startLang, endLat, endLang);
```

For eg. using `"de-DE"` locale, a number (say `204643340.34456645`) gets formatted to "204.643.340,345" but combined with commas in final return string, it looks a bit odd, like ("Route from (24,87808, 74,61229) to (24,87922, 74,61708).pdf"). 

Should I refine this more? If so, then any ideas as to how?
